{"version":1,"kind":"Article","sha256":"e881e40b279f0c52b64227709fffb241fff13f2113b4eea4e63aacacbbd28d5e","slug":"collaboration.oss-sustainability.oss-sustainability-challenges","location":"/collaboration/oss-sustainability/oss-sustainability-challenges.md","dependencies":[],"frontmatter":{"title":"Sustainability of Open Source Projects","content_includes_title":false,"authors":[{"nameParsed":{"literal":"The Turing Way Community","given":"The Turing Way","family":"Community"},"name":"The Turing Way Community","id":"contributors-myst-generated-uid-0"}],"license":{"content":{"id":"CC-BY-4.0","url":"https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","name":"Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International","free":true,"CC":true},"code":{"id":"MIT","url":"https://opensource.org/licenses/MIT","name":"MIT License","free":true,"osi":true}},"github":"https://github.com/the-turing-way/the-turing-way","copyright":"2019-2025","numbering":{"title":{"offset":1}},"edit_url":"https://github.com/the-turing-way/the-turing-way/blob/main/book/website/collaboration/oss-sustainability/oss-sustainability-challenges.md","thumbnail":"/oss-sustainability-p-7b652e98038d912665b2aa4b5aa4270c.png","exports":[{"format":"md","filename":"oss-sustainability-challenges.md","url":"/oss-sustainability-c-f26e2a940bbdf1a9e66fb72cc5c91cea.md"}]},"mdast":{"type":"root","children":[{"type":"block","children":[{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":5,"column":1},"end":{"line":6,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Early-stage projects often reach a point when funding has run out for a project that they have spent months or years developing, and they can face a daunting array of obstacles on the road to turning an academic or volunteer-led project into a robust, sustainable enterprise that will outlive its original funding source.\nIn this chapter we will outline the factors that should be considered when you want to turn a project into Open Source Software (OSS) with a self-sustaining organisation, and we will explore how different projects have achieved sustainability through a variety of organisational structures.","position":{"start":{"line":5,"column":1},"end":{"line":5,"column":1}},"key":"Az6GMS64sE"}],"key":"rguoraWhLO"},{"type":"heading","depth":2,"position":{"start":{"line":8,"column":1},"end":{"line":8,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"The big misconception about Open Source","position":{"start":{"line":8,"column":1},"end":{"line":8,"column":1}},"key":"rbvoLkJ3gc"}],"identifier":"the-big-misconception-about-open-source","label":"The big misconception about Open Source","html_id":"the-big-misconception-about-open-source","implicit":true,"key":"cHid5mpxAo"},{"type":"container","kind":"figure","children":[{"type":"image","url":"/oss-sustainability-p-7b652e98038d912665b2aa4b5aa4270c.png","alt":"A researcher is torn between taking the path of private commercialisation or the path of open source.","urlSource":"../../../figures/oss-sustainability-pathways-problem.png","key":"tglaPiIile"},{"type":"caption","children":[{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":14,"column":1},"end":{"line":14,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"captionNumber","kind":"figure","label":"oss-sustainability-pathways-problem","identifier":"oss-sustainability-pathways-problem","html_id":"oss-sustainability-pathways-problem","enumerator":"1","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Figure ","key":"dtxILUIaVT"},{"type":"text","value":"1","key":"d3HUFaUenQ"},{"type":"text","value":":","key":"t7amwyFRdH"}],"template":"Figure %s:","key":"U0ksrO6Hfc"},{"type":"text","value":"This image was created by Scriberia for The Turing Way community and is used under a CC-BY 4.0 licence for reuse. Zenodo. DOI 10.5281/zenodo.3332807","position":{"start":{"line":14,"column":1},"end":{"line":14,"column":1}},"key":"Ze4lSn3LVB"}],"key":"pkGX2vj9Pq"}],"key":"lf0syNTzA2"}],"label":"oss-sustainability-pathways-problem","identifier":"oss-sustainability-pathways-problem","enumerator":"1","html_id":"oss-sustainability-pathways-problem","key":"KGkSpTgQIM"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":17,"column":1},"end":{"line":18,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"One of the most common beliefs about Open Source is that it simply means “free” and therefore an open source project can never generate revenue or profit.\nThe ","position":{"start":{"line":17,"column":1},"end":{"line":17,"column":1}},"key":"pSvijAFAJv"},{"type":"link","url":"https://book.the-turing-way.org/reproducible-research/open.html","position":{"start":{"line":17,"column":1},"end":{"line":17,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"definition","position":{"start":{"line":17,"column":1},"end":{"line":17,"column":1}},"key":"pZ8mY2GgpK"}],"urlSource":"https://book.the-turing-way.org/reproducible-research/open.html","key":"eBN1fa4CyG"},{"type":"text","value":" used by The Turing Way states that OSS should:","position":{"start":{"line":17,"column":1},"end":{"line":17,"column":1}},"key":"TXFRD4Qknm"}],"key":"dThTVkJJqD"},{"type":"blockquote","position":{"start":{"line":19,"column":1},"end":{"line":20,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":19,"column":1},"end":{"line":19,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Be publicly available: It is difficult to use and benefit from knowledge hidden behind barriers such as passwords and paywalls.","position":{"start":{"line":19,"column":1},"end":{"line":19,"column":1}},"key":"xtcn1Nl1ih"}],"key":"BIWbhWdlWs"}],"key":"udxxXEu1ax"},{"type":"heading","depth":2,"position":{"start":{"line":22,"column":1},"end":{"line":22,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Defining project sustainability","position":{"start":{"line":22,"column":1},"end":{"line":22,"column":1}},"key":"csZBPOdyox"}],"identifier":"defining-project-sustainability","label":"Defining project sustainability","html_id":"defining-project-sustainability","implicit":true,"key":"ROLVREZ94C"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":24,"column":1},"end":{"line":26,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Narrowly-defined, a sustainable project must have funding to continue operations, which alone represents a daunting challenge to someone who wants to take their idea beyond an academic or personal project so that it can thrive on its own.\nMore broadly-defined, sustainable open source projects encompass the values of reproducibility, transparency, accessibility, and reusability while maintaining an engaged community of contributors - and this is feasible through both monetised and non-monetised routes.\nWhile OSS must be freely available, including in the monetary sense, this does not necessarily mean that a project that is run openly and sustainably cannot be monetised.","position":{"start":{"line":24,"column":1},"end":{"line":24,"column":1}},"key":"fRE0fFc1Li"}],"key":"npziLSNsd5"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":28,"column":1},"end":{"line":28,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"For instance, many of the world’s largest companies build, use and maintain open source software because open development has been shown to produce innovative, stable, and secure software tools that are in high demand around the world.","position":{"start":{"line":28,"column":1},"end":{"line":28,"column":1}},"key":"W0yKjNZFbp"}],"key":"ZVt9Eq4Qle"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":30,"column":1},"end":{"line":33,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"It can seem like there is a binary choice between commercialisation (for example, a startup or spinout company) and remaining completely open source (for example, setting up a volunteer-based community governance model.\nHowever, these two paths should not be considered mutually exclusive, and an open-source, community-governed project can work in tandem with a business based on that same project.\nThere are several pathways to generating revenue from an open source project, whether for profit or to sustain a not-for-profit enterprise.\nIn this chapter we’ll present some of key considerations when looking to make a project sustainable, and how these differ depending on the organisational structure you want to pursue.","position":{"start":{"line":30,"column":1},"end":{"line":30,"column":1}},"key":"ReKJGU5v8A"}],"key":"LON6nv6I3d"},{"type":"container","kind":"figure","children":[{"type":"image","url":"/oss-sustainability-p-6ffda6289ee0b8566b5e0ddd0ff44dce.png","alt":"A researcher considers the 4 pathways/pillars of OSS sustainability.","urlSource":"../../../figures/oss-sustainability-pathways-solution.png","key":"pkQYXxXDhW"},{"type":"caption","children":[{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":40,"column":1},"end":{"line":40,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"captionNumber","kind":"figure","label":"oss-sustainability-pathways-solution","identifier":"oss-sustainability-pathways-solution","html_id":"oss-sustainability-pathways-solution","enumerator":"2","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Figure ","key":"l1ecG3TcWu"},{"type":"text","value":"2","key":"oaqJqt7uUn"},{"type":"text","value":":","key":"lPr7zOlPJC"}],"template":"Figure %s:","key":"F5HoxhNPeX"},{"type":"text","value":"This image was created by Scriberia for The Turing Way community and is used under a CC-BY 4.0 licence for reuse. Zenodo. DOI 10.5281/zenodo.3332807","position":{"start":{"line":40,"column":1},"end":{"line":40,"column":1}},"key":"QrOLfN1nuX"}],"key":"Om5KuhCHlB"}],"key":"a9IdS70EV8"}],"label":"oss-sustainability-pathways-solution","identifier":"oss-sustainability-pathways-solution","enumerator":"2","html_id":"oss-sustainability-pathways-solution","key":"FYZ46LV8Gn"},{"type":"heading","depth":2,"position":{"start":{"line":42,"column":1},"end":{"line":42,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"First steps towards OSS sustainability","position":{"start":{"line":42,"column":1},"end":{"line":42,"column":1}},"key":"ToHjBU45Y5"}],"identifier":"first-steps-towards-oss-sustainab